<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18511027-1964">
               <interp inst="t18511027-1964" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18511027"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18511027-1964" type="date" value="18511027"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18511027-1964-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1964-18511027 t18511027-1964-offence-1 t18511027-1964-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1964. <persName id="def1-1964-18511027" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1964-18511027" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1964-18511027" type="surname" value="CHIDLOW"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1964-18511027" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">THOMAS CHIDLOW</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18511027-1964-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18511027-1964-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="royalOffences"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18511027-1964-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="coiningOffences"></interp>, unlawfully uttering counterfeit coin.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS. SCRIVEN</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">CLERK</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18511027-name-810" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-810" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-810" type="surname" value="NOBLE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-810" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES NOBLE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am conductor of one of Wilson's <hi rend="italic">Favorite</hi> omnibuses. On 9th Sept., about 11 o'clock at night, the prisoner was a passenger by my omnibus—he got on at Islington and rode to the Eagle in the City-road, about three-quarters of a mile—the fare was 4<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., and he gave me a bad half-crown—I asked him if he had any more, and he gave me a good one—I told him I should not give him the change till I saw a policeman, and I kept the bad one also—he rode on the steps to the Artillery-ground gate, about a quarter of a mile, where I saw Allen, and I gave him the bad half-crown—he was searched, but no more found on him—I asked him for his address, and he said he could be found at Mr. Bowen's, 23, Cullum-street, Fenchurch-street—I asked him if his name was Bowen—he said no, but he could be beard of there, and his name was Chidlow—I gave him the change out of the good half-crown, and Allen took the bad one—the prisoner was then allowed to go.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you been to Cullum-street? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I went to see if there was such a number in the street, and saw the name of Bowen on the door.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18511027-name-811" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-811" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-811" type="surname" value="ALLEN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-811" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE ALLEN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman, G</hi> 46). On 9th Sept. I was on duty in the City-road, and about 5 minutes to 11 o'clock saw Noble and the prisoner-Noble said he had given him a bad half-crown—I asked Noble whether he would charge him, but he would not as he could not leave his omnibus—I took the bad half-crown and marked it—this is it (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>)—I have had it ever since.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18511027-name-812" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-812" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-812" type="surname" value="FENN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-812" type="given" value="SAMUEL WILLIAM"></interp>SAMUEL WILLIAM FENN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am conductor of one of the <hi rend="italic">Atlas</hi> omnibuses. On 13th Sept. the prisoner was a passenger by my omnibus—he got up it the Bricklayers' Arms at 5 or six minutes to 10 o'clock at night, and rode for about three minutes, a quarter or half a mile—the fare was 4<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., and he gave me a counterfeit half-crown in payment—I said, "Halloo! what have you got here?" and told him it was a bad one—he said he was not aware of it—I left my omnibus, and walked with the prisoner to the Elephant and Castle, where I showed the half-crown to the time-keeper, who asked him for his address and he refused to give it—I gave the prisoner into custody to Hyde, and gave him the half-crown.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18511027-name-813" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-813" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-813" type="surname" value="HYDE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-813" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN HYDE</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman, A</hi> 484). On 13th Sept. I was on duty at the Elephant and Castle, and was called by the time-keeper, who gave me this half-crown (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>)—Fenn asked the prisoner for his name and address, and he refused to give it—I searched the prisoner, and found on him a good half-crown and the paper which is attached to the depositions; I marked it at the time—when I took it out of his pocket the inspector took it up and</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185110270161"></xptr>
               <p>began reading it—the prisoner then said, "That belongs to me in my trade as a gasfitter; it is no use to you"—(<hi rend="italic">this paper was read, at follows</hi>;—"<hi rend="italic">Jmson's</hi> 2nd <hi rend="italic">Chemistery,</hi> 2 vols <hi rend="italic">caled</hi> Elements of Arts"—"Clean the metal with gasfitters' dipping <hi rend="italic">asid emerce</hi> the metal and wash <hi rend="italic">of</hi> quick"—"To silver, moisten in common salt and water then rub or brush a little silver on with cream of <hi rend="italic">tarter and finely</hi> finish with <hi rend="italic">do.</hi> and water and dry it <hi rend="italic">of</hi> for use"—"<hi rend="italic">Disolve</hi> the silver in a cup with the best nitric acid adding a little heat"—"Precipitate the silver by throwing it in salt and water—<hi rend="italic">chang</hi> the water so long as it <hi rend="italic">tasts asid</hi> say 4 times"—"One oz of <hi rend="italic">syanide</hi> of potass in one pint of <hi rend="italic">destiled</hi> or rain water then add £ oz of lunar <hi rend="italic">custic</hi> to keep up the strength add 60 drops of sulph. <hi rend="italic">asid</hi> and fasten to the pole of the Battery some old silver.")</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18511027-name-814" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-814" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-814" type="surname" value="WEBSTER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-814" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM WEBSTER</persName>
                  </hi>. These half-crowns are both counterfeit, and differ from those usually produced in Court, inasmuch as these are struck from diet, and then plated—the second process mentioned in the paper just read would electro-plate them, which is the modern process—the first is the old process of colouring them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Which do you call the electro-plating process? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> That commencing "1 oz. <hi rend="italic">syanide</hi> potass;" that is for giving a colour to copper or brass, but not to white metal—these are made of brass—I do not know what this one means, "clean the metal," &amp;c—this, "to silver, moisten in common salt," &amp;c, is merely to cleanse either brass or copper—that would be used in any business where they have copper or brass.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLERK</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> To what does this apply, "add 60 drops of silphuric acid, and fasten to the pole of the battery?" <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> To electro-plating—I have no doubt that that is the way in which these half-crowns have been treated—there is no other way to do it. <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">called</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18511027-name-815" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-815" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-815" type="surname" value="M'GAPER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-815" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN M'GAPER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a gunmaker, of Goodman's fields—I have known the prisoner fifteen years—he is a gas-fitter, and has a shop in Lambeth—he worked in the same employment with me seven years, and I know him privately besides—he has always borne a respectable character, and has wife and family.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SCRIVEN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Where does he live? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> With his brother, I believe, in Cullum-street—I have been in almost daily communi<lb></lb>cation with him for seven or eight years.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18511027-name-816" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-816" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-816" type="surname" value="BUSH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-816" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH BUSH</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a saw-maker, of 1, Somerset-street, Aldgate—I have known the prisoner eleven years—he has always been a very upright, honest young man.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLERK</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Who is he now working for? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He had a shop of his own a few weeks ago, in Walworth; till within the last five weeks, I believe—I have never been there—he has told me he employed one man—I have no means of knowing what he has been doing during the last three months.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Has he given up this shop since this charge was made against him? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> A little before that.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18511027-name-817" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-817" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-817" type="surname" value="KEEN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-817" type="given" value="JOB"></interp>JOB KEEN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am gunmaker to the Honourable East India Company and the Board of Ordnance. I have known the prisoner ten years—he was in my employ eight years—he has borne an excellent character.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SCRIVEN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When did he leave you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Last May twelve months—I have seen him occasionally since.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18511027-name-818" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-818" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-818" type="surname" value="HARDING"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-818" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH HARDING</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a builder, at Kennington-cross. I have known the prisoner twelve months—he has done gas-fitting and smiths, work, for me—I</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185110270162"></xptr>
               <p>always found him honest—he took a furnishing ironmonger's shop of me, which he gave up six or seven weeks ago.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18511027-name-819" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-819" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-819" type="surname" value="TAYLOR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18511027-name-819" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD TAYLOR</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a coal-merchant at Vauxhall—I have known the prisoner thirteen months—he has plated and re-silvered candlesticks for me—I always found him honest.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLERK</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When did he leave his business? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Five or six weeks ago.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Two other Witnesses deposed to the prisoner's good character.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
